Sep 15 2008 	Lost some character; but still nice	We've stayed at the Connaught a couple of times before, and also used it as a quiet and relaxing place to meet up with friends and business associates - and I must say I always loved the place. That having been said, it was getting a bit creaky and although we liked the feel of staying in a mad rich old relative's house, we can see how that might not be everyone's cup of tea.This is the first time we've stayed since the renovation, and just a quick overnight stay, not wanting to have to travel home after a great dinner at Umu.The whole place is much slicker than before - some of the interventions are quite subtle, others less so. Our room was great, not overly large but with the benefit of a 'corridor' connecting the bedroom and bathroom which means you can keep a lot of your stuff out of the way. I vaguely recall some of the rooms were always configured this way, to allow interconnecting.We also had a beautiful view across Carlos Place toward Mount Street, very light and open - rare to see so much sky from a London hotel - and very quiet despite the ongoing renovations (A crane appeared outside our window in the morning, but we didn't hear it get there).The bathrooms are the real success of the refurb. At first glance similar (plenty of white marble and natural daylight with 'trad' chrome fittings) to before but much more 'luxe' and of course now everything works. Nice big bathtub (but you need to set it running at 5pm if you want a bath at 6pm) and a small LCD TV much more tastefully integrated than most.The public rooms have been completely revamped. The Connaught bar (as was) is now called Coburg and is (in design terms) rather embarrassing IMHO. It's trying to be a bit young and trendy (Opie prints on the walls etc) but looks a bit like your uncle wearing a track suit. The American bar (now confusingly the Connaught bar) is beautiful - stunning and luxurious with a strong 30s look... although I'll miss the American bar.The conservatory is a great success, lovely for lunch (as we enjoyed) but if your going for tea I'd recommend staying 'indoors' in the bit that was always there, as it's much cosier - but not as cramped as it was before the refurb/extension.OK, the negatives:- A lot of the character of the rooms has been lost. Our room had all new custom furniture which was nice enough but a bit generic and 'flat-pack' feeling (although good quality). Previously we've enjoyed antique furniture and 1930s chrome seashell light fittings, etc.- The new lighting system seems a tad problematic - ours seemed to turn off by themselves and the control panels with LED status lights seem flaky and visually incongruous. - Breakfast was spectacularly poor for a hotel at this price, and at more than GBP 70 for two, not terrific value either (we're not too badly off, but we're not so wealthy as to not notice spending GBP 70 on a not very good breakfast). Firstly, there was no option on the request form to choose Tea with your breakfast, only to choose from two types of Coffee. No tea? In an English hotel? I kid you not. I drew an extra box, marked it 'Tea' and this was accommodated.When the breakfast arrived it was cold, the poached eggs had runny whites (I hate that), the sausage wasn't cooked and the mushrooms were very nasty, sweaty things such as you mind find in a tin. The pastries were mostly burned, but a generous selection. And the positives:- it's a unique place and has retained some of its character despite everything. It's very homely and relaxing but sophisticated as well, in a very quiet, relaxing and luxurious part of London that's nevertheless very close to great shopping, dining and so on.- The 'butler' - an idea I didn't like at all - was in fact very helpful and indeed the service overall was great - if surprisingly informal.- The bathroom's great (once the tub has filled).- The beds are very comfortable, and it's quiet - which are the most important things after all.So, all in all, it's a shame to lose some of the character but things change and it's better that everything works. Still love the place and will doubtless be back but hope the breakfast is better...	
